{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L1sHNdRkmVyui3VM2yUHEM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# InPracSys — Product Research\n     2→\n     3→Researched: 2026-02-14\n     4→Developer website: https://www.inpracsys.com\n     5→\n     6→## Overview\n     7→\n     8→InPracSys (legal name: Innovative Practice Systems, Inc.) is a very small, niche EHR vendor headquartered at 2225 Lyndale Ave S, Minneapolis, MN 55405. Founded in 2003 by Dr. Ashu Kataria, the company has approximately 25 employees and an estimated annual revenue under $1 million (per Buzzfile). The product is built specifically for urology practices, with the tagline \"built by urologists, with urologists in mind.\" Despite its small size, the product carries a broad ONC certification across 35 criteria.\n     9→\n    10→Kataria also serves as CEO of RiskAssistMD (since 2018), a related company at the same address focused on reducing medical malpractice liability. The relationship between the two companies is unclear — RiskAssistMD may be a productization of InPracSys's Risk Management module. No funding history was found; the company is likely bootstrapped. InPracSys has essentially no market visibility: zero reviews on G2, Capterra, Software Advice, or KLAS, no press coverage, and only one identifiable customer from their own demo page.\n    11→\n    12→## Product: InPracSys EHR\n    13→\n    14→CHPL ID: 10194 (15.05.05.2762.INPS.01.00.1.191206)\n    15→Version: 9.0\n    16→Certification Date: 2019-12-06\n    17→\n    18→### What It Is\n    19→\n    20→InPracSys EHR is a cloud-based, full-featured EHR system designed primarily for urology practices. The certified module appears to be the whole product — there is no indication of a larger platform or separate certified components. It is accessed via web browser (any major browser), iPad, iPhone, and Android. The system uses a proprietary \"Point and Click\" single-page interface to minimize keyboarding, with a \"FastCharting\" feature that claims to allow documentation of a full renal stone consultation (HPI, ICD-10, orders, MU, PQRS, E/M codes) in under 30 seconds.\n    21→\n    22→The system comes preloaded with urology-specific templates and forms. The Real World Testing documentation explicitly states: \"Our application is specific to the practice of Urology.\" While the vendor website claims support for other specialties (Cardiology, Dermatology, Gastroenterology, OB-Gyn, Ophthalmology, Pulmonology), there is no evidence of actual deployment outside urology.\n    23→\n    24→### Users & Market\n    25→\n    26→**Target users:** Urologists, urology clinic staff, and their patients. The product targets small to mid-size urology practices.\n    27→\n    28→**Known customer:** Comprehensive Urologic Care, S.C. in Lake Barrington, Illinois (with locations in Elgin and Hoffman Estates, IL) — identified through InPracSys's own demo page, which hosts a patient portal for this practice at `azcucptportal.inpracsys.com`.\n    29→\n    30→**Customer base size:** Unknown, but almost certainly very small. The Real World Testing reports use a sample size of only 10 transactions per criterion, tested at a single \"representative clinic.\" The RWT documents acknowledge that some certification criteria go unused by the testing clinic and must be tested in \"InPracSys Lab\" instead. This strongly suggests very limited deployment — possibly single-digit clinic customers.\n    31→\n    32→**Market visibility:** No reviews on any major platform. No press coverage. No industry analyst mentions. No customer testimonials retrievable from the vendor's own site. The homepage mentions promoting attendance at the 2026 AUA Annual Meeting (Washington D.C., May 15–18, 2026), but no evidence of InPracSys as an exhibitor was found.\n    33→\n    34→### Modules & Functionality\n    35→\n    36→The following modules and features are described on the vendor website:\n    37→\n    38→- **EHR / MyEMR (Core Charting):** Single-page interface with point-and-click documentation, urology-specific templates, mobile access, voice dictation via Siri/Cortana. Preloaded with urology-specific forms and clinical content.\n    39→\n    40→- **FastCharting:** Rapid documentation tool — the vendor claims a full renal stone consult can be charted in under 30 seconds. This is the product's primary differentiator.\n    41→\n    42→- **Care Pathways / PRACTICE iQ:** Stepped therapy programs aligned with national guidelines. Identifies qualifying patients for high-value drug programs, manages pre-authorization and billing. The vendor claims this generates $2,500–$7,500 per patient annually in additional revenue. This appears to be a significant revenue-generating feature for urology practices.\n    43→\n    44→- **Risk Management:** Clinical decision support with automated alerts for urology-specific scenarios (e.g., stents placed but not removed, missed scrotal ultrasounds). Available as a standalone product for clinics using other EHRs. This module appears related to the separate RiskAssistMD company.\n    45→\n    46→- **Billing:** Superbill generation, Level 1 coding, professional component anatomical pathology billing. The vendor claims a 99% clean claim rate. This appears to be billing/superbill generation within the EHR, not a full practice management/RCM system.\n    47→\n    48→- **E-Prescribing:** Via SureScripts Rx HUB integration.\n    49→\n    50→- **Patient Portal:** Patient-facing portal for medical records access, appointments, correspondence/messaging, and account management.\n    51→\n    52→- **Data Mining / Analytics:** Custom reporting for clinical trial candidate identification and value-based payment outcome analysis.\n    53→\n    54→- **Clinical Trials:** Automates patient identification for clinical trials and manages trial documentation.\n    55→\n    56→- **Telemedicine:** Telehealth capabilities mentioned but details are sparse.\n    57→\n    58→- **Meaningful Use / CQM Reporting:** Built-in attestation dashboard, automated CQM/PQRS reporting.\n    59→\n    60→- **Integration:** Interfaces with labs, hospitals, SureScripts, and existing practice management systems. Claims to eliminate duplicate data entry. Technology partners include SureScripts, eProviderSolutions, DoseSpot (e-prescribing), and Dragon/Nuance (speech recognition).\n    61→\n    62→- **FHIR API:** Patient/provider API access (security-restricted). API documentation is hosted at `ipsemrapi.inpracsys.com`.\n    63→\n    64→### Data & Content\n    65→\n    66→Based on certified criteria, vendor feature descriptions, and product pages, InPracSys EHR manages the following data:\n    67→\n    68→**Clinical Data:**\n    69→- Patient demographics (certified (a)(5))\n    70→- Problem lists / diagnoses with ICD-10 coding (certified (a)(6))\n    71→- Medication lists and e-prescriptions via SureScripts (certified (a)(7), (a)(10))\n    72→- Medication allergy lists (certified (a)(8))\n    73→- Clinical notes and encounter documentation — HPI, ROS, exam, assessment/plan (per FastCharting feature descriptions)\n    74→- Urology-specific clinical data — the vendor explicitly mentions urine analysis, bladder scans, and TRUS (transrectal ultrasound) results in feature descriptions\n    75→- Lab orders and results (certified (a)(2), (a)(3))\n    76→- Diagnostic imaging orders/results (certified (a)(3))\n    77→- Vital signs (certified (a)(4))\n    78→- Smoking status (certified (a)(11))\n    79→- Family health history (certified (a)(12))\n    80→- Implantable device data (certified (a)(14))\n    81→- Clinical decision support rules and risk alerts (certified (a)(9); also the Risk Management module with urology-specific rules like stent tracking)\n    82→\n    83→**Administrative/Financial Data:**\n    84→- E/M coding data (per FastCharting feature)\n    85→- Superbills and billing records (per Billing module description)\n    86→- Claims data (vendor cites 99% clean claim rate)\n    87→- Pre-authorization records (per Care Pathways/PRACTICE iQ module)\n    88→- Professional component anatomical pathology billing records\n    89→\n    90→**Care Coordination Data:**\n    91→- C-CDA documents for transitions of care (certified (b)(1), (b)(2))\n    92→- Clinical information reconciliation data (certified (b)(2))\n    93→- Electronic referral records (certified (b)(3))\n    94→- Direct messaging (certified (h)(1))\n    95→- Care pathway / stepped therapy tracking and patient qualification records (per PRACTICE iQ module)\n    96→\n    97→**Quality/Compliance Data:**\n    98→- Clinical quality measures (CQMs) (certified (c)(1))\n    99→- PQRS measures\n   100→- Meaningful Use attestation data\n   101→\n   102→**Patient-Facing Data:**\n   103→- Patient portal records — view/download/transmit (certified (e)(1))\n   104→- Appointment scheduling records\n   105→- Patient-provider messaging/correspondence (per patient portal description)\n   106→- Patient account management data\n   107→\n   108→**Public Health Data:**\n   109→- Syndromic surveillance data (certified (f)(2))\n   110→- Electronic case reporting data (certified (f)(5))\n   111→\n   112→**Research Data:**\n   113→- Clinical trial candidate identification data (per Clinical Trials module)\n   114→- Data mining / analytics outputs (per Data Mining module)\n   115→\n   116→**Notable gaps in information:** The website does not clearly describe whether the billing module is a full practice management system or just superbill/coding generation. The relationship between InPracSys billing and external practice management systems is unclear — the integration page mentions interfacing with \"existing practice management systems,\" suggesting billing may be supplementary rather than comprehensive. It's also unclear whether the product stores scanned documents, images (e.g., cystoscopy images), or other unstructured content typical in urology workflows.\n   117→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. Founded in 2003 by Dr. Ashu Kataria, the company has approximately 25 employees and an estimated annual revenue under $1 million (per Buzzfile). The product is built specifically for urology practices, with the tagline \"built by urologists, with urologists in mind.\" Despite its small size, the product carries a broad ONC certification across 35 criteria.\n\nKataria also serves as CEO of RiskAssistMD (since 2018), a related company at the same address focused on reducing medical malpractice liability. The relationship between the two companies is unclear — RiskAssistMD may be a productization of InPracSys's Risk Management module. No funding history was found; the company is likely bootstrapped. InPracSys has essentially no market visibility: zero reviews on G2, Capterra, Software Advice, or KLAS, no press coverage, and only one identifiable customer from their own demo page.\n\n## Product: InPracSys EHR\n\nCHPL ID: 10194 (15.05.05.2762.INPS.01.00.1.191206)\nVersion: 9.0\nCertification Date: 2019-12-06\n\n### What It Is\n\nInPracSys EHR is a cloud-based, full-featured EHR system designed primarily for urology practices. The certified module appears to be the whole product — there is no indication of a larger platform or separate certified components. It is accessed via web browser (any major browser), iPad, iPhone, and Android. The system uses a proprietary \"Point and Click\" single-page interface to minimize keyboarding, with a \"FastCharting\" feature that claims to allow documentation of a full renal stone consultation (HPI, ICD-10, orders, MU, PQRS, E/M codes) in under 30 seconds.\n\nThe system comes preloaded with urology-specific templates and forms. The Real World Testing documentation explicitly states: \"Our application is specific to the practice of Urology.\" While the vendor website claims support for other specialties (Cardiology, Dermatology, Gastroenterology, OB-Gyn, Ophthalmology, Pulmonology), there is no evidence of actual deployment outside urology.\n\n### Users & Market\n\n**Target users:** Urologists, urology clinic staff, and their patients. The product targets small to mid-size urology practices.\n\n**Known customer:** Comprehensive Urologic Care, S.C. in Lake Barrington, Illinois (with locations in Elgin and Hoffman Estates, IL) — identified through InPracSys's own demo page, which hosts a patient portal for this practice at `azcucptportal.inpracsys.com`.\n\n**Customer base size:** Unknown, but almost certainly very small. The Real World Testing reports use a sample size of only 10 transactions per criterion, tested at a single \"representative clinic.\" The RWT documents acknowledge that some certification criteria go unused by the testing clinic and must be tested in \"InPracSys Lab\" instead. This strongly suggests very limited deployment — possibly single-digit clinic customers.\n\n**Market visibility:** No reviews on any major platform. No press coverage. No industry analyst mentions. No customer testimonials retrievable from the vendor's own site. The homepage mentions promoting attendance at the 2026 AUA Annual Meeting (Washington D.C., May 15–18, 2026), but no evidence of InPracSys as an exhibitor was found.\n\n### Modules & Functionality\n\nThe following modules and features are described on the vendor website:\n\n- **EHR / MyEMR (Core Charting):** Single-page interface with point-and-click documentation, urology-specific templates, mobile access, voice dictation via Siri/Cortana. Preloaded with urology-specific forms and clinical content.\n\n- **FastCharting:** Rapid documentation tool — the vendor claims a full renal stone consult can be charted in under 30 seconds. This is the product's primary differentiator.\n\n- **Care Pathways / PRACTICE iQ:** Stepped therapy programs aligned with national guidelines. Identifies qualifying patients for high-value drug programs, manages pre-authorization and billing. The vendor claims this generates $2,500–$7,500 per patient annually in additional revenue. This appears to be a significant revenue-generating feature for urology practices.\n\n- **Risk Management:** Clinical decision support with automated alerts for urology-specific scenarios (e.g., stents placed but not removed, missed scrotal ultrasounds). Available as a standalone product for clinics using other EHRs. This module appears related to the separate RiskAssistMD company.\n\n- **Billing:** Superbill generation, Level 1 coding, professional component anatomical pathology billing. The vendor claims a 99% clean claim rate. This appears to be billing/superbill generation within the EHR, not a full practice management/RCM system.\n\n- **E-Prescribing:** Via SureScripts Rx HUB integration.\n\n- **Patient Portal:** Patient-facing portal for medical records access, appointments, correspondence/messaging, and account management.\n\n- **Data Mining / Analytics:** Custom reporting for clinical trial candidate identification and value-based payment outcome analysis.\n\n- **Clinical Trials:** Automates patient identification for clinical trials and manages trial documentation.\n\n- **Telemedicine:** Telehealth capabilities mentioned but details are sparse.\n\n- **Meaningful Use / CQM Reporting:** Built-in attestation dashboard, automated CQM/PQRS reporting.\n\n- **Integration:** Interfaces with labs, hospitals, SureScripts, and existing practice management systems. Claims to eliminate duplicate data entry. Technology partners include SureScripts, eProviderSolutions, DoseSpot (e-prescribing), and Dragon/Nuance (speech recognition).\n\n- **FHIR API:** Patient/provider API access (security-restricted). API documentation is hosted at `ipsemrapi.inpracsys.com`.\n\n### Data & Content\n\nBased on certified criteria, vendor feature descriptions, and product pages, InPracSys EHR manages the following data:\n\n**Clinical Data:**\n- Patient demographics (certified (a)(5))\n- Problem lists / diagnoses with ICD-10 coding (certified (a)(6))\n- Medication lists and e-prescriptions via SureScripts (certified (a)(7), (a)(10))\n- Medication allergy lists (certified (a)(8))\n- Clinical notes and encounter documentation — HPI, ROS, exam, assessment/plan (per FastCharting feature descriptions)\n- Urology-specific clinical data — the vendor explicitly mentions urine analysis, bladder scans, and TRUS (transrectal ultrasound) results in feature descriptions\n- Lab orders and results (certified (a)(2), (a)(3))\n- Diagnostic imaging orders/results (certified (a)(3))\n- Vital signs (certified (a)(4))\n- Smoking status (certified (a)(11))\n- Family health history (certified (a)(12))\n- Implantable device data (certified (a)(14))\n- Clinical decision support rules and risk alerts (certified (a)(9); also the Risk Management module with urology-specific rules like stent tracking)\n\n**Administrative/Financial Data:**\n- E/M coding data (per FastCharting feature)\n- Superbills and billing records (per Billing module description)\n- Claims data (vendor cites 99% clean claim rate)\n- Pre-authorization records (per Care Pathways/PRACTICE iQ module)\n- Professional component anatomical pathology billing records\n\n**Care Coordination Data:**\n- C-CDA documents for transitions of care (certified (b)(1), (b)(2))\n- Clinical information reconciliation data (certified (b)(2))\n- Electronic referral records (certified (b)(3))\n- Direct messaging (certified (h)(1))\n- Care pathway / stepped therapy tracking and patient qualification records (per PRACTICE iQ module)\n\n**Quality/Compliance Data:**\n- Clinical quality measures (CQMs) (certified (c)(1))\n- PQRS measures\n- Meaningful Use attestation data\n\n**Patient-Facing Data:**\n- Patient portal records — view/download/transmit (certified (e)(1))\n- Appointment scheduling records\n- Patient-provider messaging/correspondence (per patient portal description)\n- Patient account management data\n\n**Public Health Data:**\n- Syndromic surveillance data (certified (f)(2))\n- Electronic case reporting data (certified (f)(5))\n\n**Research Data:**\n- Clinical trial candidate identification data (per Clinical Trials module)\n- Data mining / analytics outputs (per Data Mining module)\n\n**Notable gaps in information:** The website does not clearly describe whether the billing module is a full practice management system or just superbill/coding generation. The relationship between InPracSys billing and external practice management systems is unclear — the integration page mentions interfacing with \"existing practice management systems,\" suggesting billing may be supplementary rather than comprehensive. It's also unclear whether the product stores scanned documents, images (e.g., cystoscopy images), or other unstructured content typical in urology workflows.\n","numLines":117,"startLine":1,"totalLines":117}}}

More information can be found at the\nFHIR website\n.\nThe InPracSys FHIR API is based on FHIR V4, of the FHIR standard. Updates and definitions for use of the standard can be found on the Link:\nFHIR V4\n.\nThe EHI export contains available electronic health information for a single patient or multiple patients in computable file format. The export(s) can be downloaded as a zip file containing .xml file(s).\nSecurity\nLike many RESTful APIs, the InPracSys FHIR API uses OAuth 2 for security. This means that when making calls to any resource with the InPracSys FHIR API, you must pass a Bearer token. This token is passed in the Authorization Header.\nAuthorization: Bearer eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsIng1dCI6IjJaUXBKM1VwYmpBWVhZR2FYRUpsOGxWMF...\nTo obtain a Bearer token, you must call an Authorization Server. The authorization server typically exposes two endpoints:\nauthorize: typically used to confirm the user’s credentials\ntoken: used to obtain the Bearer token\nAs per the FHIR specification, the InPracSys FHIR API supports JSON. we limit our examples to JSON.\nOverview\nStep 1: Search for a patient\nNow that we have the Bearer token, we can call the API. See below for more information.\nA DAF DiagnosticReport is returned.\nName\nType\nCardinality\nDescription\nidentifier\n0..*\nLocal ID assigned to the report by the order filler, usually by the information system of the diagnostic service provider. You must know what identifier to use when making queries about this report from the source laboratory and for linking to the report outside FHIR context. Alternate name: ReportID.\nstatus\ncode\n1..1\nStatus of the diagnostic report as a whole. Diagnostic services routinely issue provisional/incomplete reports, and sometimes withdraw previously released reports. This is labeled as \"Is Modifier\" because applications need to take appropriate action if a report is withdrawn. The codes shall be taken from the DiagnosticReportStatus value set, which includes the following statuses: Registered, Partial, Final, Corrected, Appended, Cancelled, and Entered-in-Error. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/diagnostic-report-status.\ncategory\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nCode that classifies the clinical discipline, department, or diagnostic service that created the report. For example, cardiology, biochemistry, hematology, or MRI. This is used for searching, sorting, and displaying purposes. The level of granularity is defined by the category concepts in the DiagnosticServiceSectionCodes value set. More filtering is performed using the metadata and/or terminology hierarchy in DiagnosticReport.code. Alternate names: Department, Sub-department, service, discipline. Example codes include: AU- Audiology, CH- Chemistry, MB- Microbiology, and HM- Hematology. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/diagnostic-service-sections.\ncode\nCodeableConcept\n1..1\nTest, panel, or battery that was ordered. The typical patterns for codes are: 1) a LOINC code either as a translation from a \"local\" code or as a primary code, 2) a local code only if no suitable LOINC exists, or 3) both the local and the LOINC translation. Systems shall be capable of sending the local code if one exists. The codes shall be taken from US Laboratory Observation Profile Observation Name Codes. Other codes may be used where these codes are not suitable. This value set has more than 1000 codes. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/report-codes.\nsubject\nReference(Patient, Group, Device, Location)\n1..1\nSubject of the report. Usually this is a patient. However, diagnostic services also perform analyses on specimens collected from a variety of other sources.\nencounter\nReference(Encounter)\n0..1\nLink to the healthcare event (encounter) when the order was made.\neffectiveDateTime\ndateTime\n1..1\nSpecimen Collection Datetime which is the physically relevant dateTime for laboratory tests. If the diagnostic procedure was performed on the patient, this is the time it was performed. If there are specimens, the diagnostically relevant time can be derived from the specimen collection times, but the specimen information is not always available, and the exact relationship between the specimens and the diagnostically relevant time is not always automatic.\neffectivePeriod\nPeriod\n1..1\nSpecimen Collection Period which is the physically relevant dateTime for laboratory tests. If the diagnostic procedure was performed on the patient, this is the time it was performed. If there are specimens, the diagnostically relevant time can be derived from the specimen collection times, but the specimen information is not always available, and the exact relationship between the specimens and the diagnostically relevant time is not always automatic. If the start element is missing, the start of the period is not known. If the end element is missing, it means that the period is ongoing, or the start may be in the past, and the end date in the future, which means that period is expected/planned to end at the specified time.\nissued\nHl7.Fhir.Model.Instant\n1..1\nDate and time that this version of the report was released from the source diagnostic service. Clinicians must be able to check the date that the report was released. This may be different from the update time of the resource itself, because that is the status of the record (potentially a secondary copy), not the actual release time of the report. Alternate names: Date Created, Date published, Date Issued.\nperformer\nReference(Practitioner, Organization)\n1..1\nDiagnostic service that is responsible for issuing the report. This is helpful to know who to contact if there are queries about the results. You may need to track the source of reports for secondary data analysis. This is not necessarily the source of the atomic data items. It is the entity that takes responsibility for the clinical report. Alternate names: Laboratory, Service, Practitioner, Department, Company.\nrequest\nReference(DiagnosticOrder, ProcedureRequest, ReferralRequest)\n1..*\nDetails concerning a test or procedure requested. You need to be able to track completion of requests based on reports issued and also to report what diagnostic tests were requested (not always the same as what is delivered). You need to be able to track completion of requests based on reports issued and also to report what diagnostic tests were requested (not always the same as what is delivered).\nspecimen\nReference(Specimen)\n0..*\nDetails about the specimens on which this diagnostic report is based. If the specimen is sufficiently specified with a code in the test result name, then this additional data may be redundant. If there are multiple specimens, these may be represented per observation or group.\nresult\nReference(Observation)\n0..*\nObservations that are part of this diagnostic report. Observations can be simple name/value pairs (for example, \"atomic\" results), or they can be grouping observations that include references to other members of the group (such as \"panels\"). You need to support individual results, or report groups of results, where the result grouping is arbitrary, but meaningful. This structure is recursive in that observations can contain observations. Alternate names: Data, Atomic Value, Result, Atomic result, Data, Test, Analyte, Battery, or Organizer.\nimagingStudy\nReference(ImagingStudy, ImagingObjectSelection)\n0..*\nOne or more links to full details of any imaging performed during the diagnostic investigation. Typically, this is imaging performed by DICOM enabled modalities, but this is not required. A fully enabled PACS viewer can use this information to provide views of the source images. ImagingStudy and ImageObjectStudy and the image element are somewhat overlapping - typically, the list of image references in the image element will also be found in one of the imaging study resources. However each caters to different types of displays for different types of purposes. Neither, either, or both may be provided.\nimage\n0..*\nList of key images associated with this report. The images are generally created during the diagnostic process, and may be directly of the patient, or of treated specimens (for example, slides of interest).\nimage.comment\nstring\n0..1\nComment about the image. Typically this is used to provide an explanation for why the image is included, or to draw the viewer's attention to important features. The provider of the report should make a comment about each image included in the report. The comment should be displayed with the image. It would be common for the report to include additional discussion of the image contents in other sections such as the conclusion.\nimage.link\nReference(Media)\n1..1\nReference to the image source.\nconclusion\nstring\n0..1\nConcise and clinically contextualized narrative interpretation of the diagnostic report. You need to be able to provide a conclusion that is not lost among the basic result data. Typically, a report is either [all data, no narrative (e.g. Core lab)] or [a mix of data with some concluding narrative (e.g. Structured Pathology Report, Bone Density)], or [all narrative (e.g. typical imaging report, histopathology)]. In all of these cases, the narrative goes in \"text\".\ncodedDiagnosis\nCodeableConcept\n0..*\nCodes for the conclusion which are SNOMED CT findings codes provided as adjunct diagnosis to the report. The codes should be taken from SNOMED CT Clinical Findings. Included are codes from http://snomed.info/sct where concept is-a 404684003. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/clinical-findings.\npresentedForm\nHl7.Fhir.Model.Attachment\n0..*\nRich text representation of the entire result as issued by the diagnostic service. Multiple formats are allowed but they shall be semantically equivalent. This gives the laboratory the ability to provide its own fully formatted report for clinical fidelity. Note: \"application/pdf\" is recommended as the most reliable and interoperable in this context.\nSearching by Date\nDates are passed as query paramters on the URL. Since the URL parameters cannot handle comparators (for example, >, <=) these are passed in as part of the date.\nfromdate<=2016-01-01\ntodate=>2016-12-31\nTo search for a date range, pass in the date twice.\ne.g. fromdate<=2010-01-01&todate=>2010-12-31\nThis search would include every day in the year 2010.\nSample The logical ID is found as the result of a search.\nGET https://fhirips.azurehealthcareapis.com/Observation?pid=B3fdg1utB9Y8%3d\nGET https://fhirips.azurehealthcareapis.com/Observation?pid=B3fdg1utB9Y8%3d\nName\nRequired?\nType\nDescription\npid\nyes\nURL\nThe logical ID of the patient. Allows observations to be distinguished and referenced.\nstatus\ncode\n1..1\nThe status of the vital sign result value. The status of individual results needs to be tracked. Some results are finalized before the whole report is finalized. The conformance on this value set is required. Values include: Registered, Preliminary, Final, Amended, Cancelled, Entered in Error, and Unknown. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-status\ncategory\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nClassification of type of observation. Clinical observations measure the body's basic functions such as such as blood pressure, heart rate, respiratory rate, height, weight, body mass index, head circumference, pulse oximetry, temperature, and body surface area. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-category\ncode\nCodeableConcept\n1..1\nThis identifies the vital sign result type. Coded responses are from C-CDA Vital Sign Results. 1. Shall contain exactly one [1..1] code, where the @code should be selected from ValueSet HITSP Vital Sign Result Type. This value set indicates the allowed vital sign result types. The vocabulary selected for this value set aligns with requirements in the Meaningful Use (MU) Stage 2. Note the concept Blood pressure systolic and diastolic (55284-4) is used to group the related observations Systolic blood pressure (8480-6) and Diastolic blood pressure (8462-4). It shall not be used alone, but both 8480-6 and 8462-2 shall also be valued. The codes shall be taken from C-CDA Vital Sign Result; other codes may be used where these codes are not suitable. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-codes\nsubject\nReference(Patient, Group, Device, Location)\n0..1\nWho and/or what this vital is for. The patient, or group of patients, location, or device whose characteristics (direct or indirect) are described by the observation and into whose record the observation is placed. Indirect characteristics may be those of a specimen, fetus, donor, other observer (for example a relative or EMT), or any observation made about the subject. Observations have no value if you don't know who or what they're about. Note: One would expect this element to be a cardinality of 1..1. The only circumstance in which the subject can be missing is when the observation is made by a device that does not know the patient. In this case, the observation shall be matched to a patient through some context/channel matching technique, and at this point, the observation should be updated.\nencounter\nReference(Encounter)\n0..1\nThe healthcare event (for example, a patient and healthcare provider interaction) during which this vital was obtained. Often a dateTime for Vital Signs is preferred but if it is a historical instance, then a time period is sufficient.\nissued\nHl7.Fhir.Model.Instant\n0..1\nDate/Time this was made available.\nperformer\nReference(Practitioner, Organization, Patient, RelatedPerson)\n0..*\nWho is responsible for the observation or obtaining the vital sign. The codes shall be taken from Common UCUM units as defined in http://unitsofmeasure.org Examples include % (percent), cm (centimeter), kg (kilogram), mm(Hg) (millimeter of mercury), /min (per minute) and kg/m2 (kilogram). Note: Normally, an observation will have either a value or a set of related observations. A few observations (e.g. Apgar score) may have both a value and related observations (for an Apgar score, the observations from which the measure is derived). Knowing what values are considered \"normal\" can help evaluate the significance of a particular result. Need to be able to provide multiple reference ranges for different contexts. Most observations only have one generic reference range. Systems may choose to restrict to only supplying the relevant reference range based on knowledge about the patient (for example, specific to the patient's age, gender, weight, and other factors), but this may not be possible or appropriate. This can be a target date (or partial) or a duration of time.\ntargetQuantity\nQuantity\n0..1\nReach goal on or before. Indicates either the date or the duration after start by which the goal should be met. This identifies when the goal should be evaluated. This can be a target date (or partial) or a duration of time.\ncategory\nCodeableConcept\n0..*\nIndicates a category the goal falls within, and allows goals to be filtered and sorted based on a particular category. Examples of category include: Treatment, Dietary, or Behavioral. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/goal-category.\ndescription\nstring\n1..1\nDesired outcome. This is a human-readable description of a specific desired objective of care. Without a description of what's trying to be achieved, the element has no purpose.\nstatus\ncode\n1..1\nIndicates whether the goal has been reached and is still considered relevant. Options include: Proposed, Planned, Accepted, Rejected, In-progress, Achieved, Sustaining, On-hold, and Cancelled. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/goal-status.\nstatusDate\ndate)\n0..1\nWhen goal status took effect. This identifies the current status. For example, when the goal was initially created, when the goal was achieved, when the goal was cancelled, and so on.\nstatusReason\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nCaptures the reason for the current status. This is typically captured for statuses such as Rejected, On-hold, or Cancelled but could be present for others. Conformance is set as example. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/goal-status-reason.\nauthor\nReference( Patient, Practitioner- https://www.hl7.org/fhir/Practitioner.html or Related Person- https://www.hl7.org/fhir/RelatedPerson.html\n0..1\nWho is responsible for creating the goal. This indicates whose goal this is: patient goal, practitioner goal, related person goal, and so on. This is the individual responsible for establishing the goal, not necessarily who recorded it. (For that, use the provenance resource.)\npriority\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nIdentifies the mutually agreed level of importance associated with reaching and/or sustaining the goal. This is used for sorting and presenting goals. Extensions are available to track priorities as established by each participant. For example, priority from the patient's perspective, different practitioners' perspectives, or family member's perspectives. The ordinal extension on coding can be used to convey a numerically comparable ranking to priority. Conformance is preferred and defines the following codes: High, Medium, and Low. Different coding systems may use \"low value=important.\" For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/goal-priority.\naddresses\nReference(Condition, Observation, MedicationStatement, NutritionOrder, ProcedureRequest, RiskAssessment)\n0..*\nIdentified conditions and other health record elements that are intended to be addressed by the goal. This allows specific goals to be explicitly linked to the concerns they're dealing with which makes the goal more understandable. Reference profiles include: Condition, Observation, MedicationStatement, NutritionOrder, ProcedureRequest, and RiskAssessment.\nnote\nAnnotation\n0..*\nComments or annotation about the goal. Must capture information about the goal that doesn't actually describe the goal. May be used for progress notes, concerns, or other related information that doesn't actually describe the goal itself. This is also an MU requirement, which determines the narrative portion of the goal.\noutcome\n0..*\nThe end result of goal. Outcome identifies the change (or lack of change) at the point where the goal was deemed to be cancelled or achieved. Outcome tracking is a key aspect of care planning. Note that this should not duplicate the goal status.\noutcome.resultCodeableConcept\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nCode or observation that resulted from goal.\noutcome.resultReference\nReference(Observation)\n0..1\nCode or observation that resulted from the goal. This describes what has or has not changed. GoalOutcome: The result of the goal. For example, \"25% increase in shoulder mobility,\" \"Anxiety reduced to moderate levels,\" or \"15 kg weight loss sustained over 6 months.\"\nSearching by Date\nDates are passed in as Query paramters on the URL. Since the URL parameters cannot handle comparators (e.g. >, <=) these are passed in as pat of the date\nfromdate<=2016-01-01\ntodate=>2016-12-31\nTo search for a date range, pass in the date twice.\ne.g. fromdate<=2010-01-01&todate=>2010-12-31\nThis search would include every day in the year 2010.\nSample Output\n{\"resourceType\":\"Goal\",\"id\":\"9H8hiMj2TTM%3d\",\"identifier\":[{\"value\":\"9H8hiMj2TTM%3d\"}],\"status\":\"on-hold\",\"priority\":{\"coding\":[{\"system\":\"http://hl7.org/fhir/goal-priority\",\"code\":\"high-priority\",\"display\":\"High Priority\"}],\"text\":\"high\"},\"description\":{\"text\":\"Get rid of intermittent fever that is occurring every few weeks. Need to gain more energy to do reg\"},\"subject\":{\"reference\":\"fhirips.azurehealthcareapis.com/Patient?_id=B3fdg1utB9Y8%3d\",\"display\":\"Rosdel Jamie\"},\"startDate\":\"2017-05-01\"}\nExpected Exceptions\nI). Invalid Patient ID (Patient ID is the Mandatory parameter)\nII).If the patient does not have Patient Goal data, empty bundle json will return.\nHealth Concern\nDetailed information about health concerns\nRetrieving a patient’s health concerns\nThe logical ID (of the patient to retrieve) is passed as part of the URL. The logical ID is found as the result of a search.\nGET https://fhirips.azurehealthcareapis.com/HealthcareService?pid=B3fdg1utB9Y8%3d\nName\nRequired?\nType\nDescription\npid\nyes\nURL\nPatient's logical ID. This is retrieved using the search function.\nA DAF Condition (Problem) is retuned\nName\nType\nCardinality\nDescription\nidentifier\n0..*\nIdentifier associated with this condition that are defined by business processes and/or used to refer to it when a direct URL reference to the resource itself is not appropriate. For example, in CDA documents or in written/printed documentation.\npatient\nReference(Patient)\n1..1\nIndicates the patient who the condition record is associated with. This defines constraints and extensions on the patient resource for use in querying and retrieving patient demographic information.\nencounter\nReference(Encounter)\n0..1\nEncounter during which the condition was first asserted.\nasserter\nReference(Practitioner, Patient)\n0..1\nIndividual who is making the condition statement. This could be a provider or patient reference.\ndateRecorded\ndate)\n0..1\nIndicates the date when this particular condition record was created in the EHR, not the date of the most recent update in terms of when severity, abatement, and so forth were specified. The date of the last record modification can be retrieved from the resource metadata.\ncode\nCodeableConcept\n1..1\nIdentification of the condition, problem, or diagnosis. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/condition-code.\ncategory\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nA category assigned to the condition. The categorization is often highly contextual and may appear poorly differentiated or not very useful in other contexts. The value set conformance is preferred and options include: Complaint, Symptom, Finding, and Diagnosis. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/condition-category.\nclinicalStatus\ncode\n0..1\nThe clinical status of the condition. The value set conformance is preferred and options include: Active, Relapse, Remission, and Resolved. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/condition-clinical\nverificationStatus\ncode\n1..1\nThe verification status of the condition or rather, the verification status to support or decline the clinical status of the condition or diagnosis. The value set conformance is required and options include: Provisional, Differential, Confirmed, Refuted, Entered-in-error, and Unknown. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/condition-ver-status.\nseverity\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nSubjective severity of condition. The value set conformance is extensible and options include: Fatal, Severe, Moderate, and Mild. Extensions are allowed. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/condition-severity.\nonsetDateTime\ndateTime\n0..1\nEstimated or actual date, date-time, or age. A date, when the Condition statement was documented. The Date Recorded represents the date when this particular Condition record was created in the EHR, not the date of the most recent update in terms of when severity, abatement, etc. were specified. The date of the last record modification can be retrieved from the resource metadata.\nonsetQuantity\nQuantity\n0..1\nThere shall be a code if there is a value and it shall be an expression of time. If system is present, it shall be UCUM. If value is present, it shall be positive. The context of use may frequently define what kind of quantity this is and therefore what kind of units can be used. In this case, it is used to define the onset of the condition.\nonsetPeriod\nPeriod\n0..1\nA time period defined by a start and end date/time. A period specifies a range of times. The context of use will specify whether the entire range applies (for example, \"the patient was an inpatient of the hospital for this time range\") or one value from the period applies For example, \"give to the patient between 2 and 4 pm on 24-Jun 2013.\"\nonsetRange\nHl7.Fhir.Model.Range\n0..1\nA set of ordered Quantity values defined by a low and high limit. A Range specifies a set of possible values; usually, one value from the range applies. For example, \"give the patient between 2 and 4 tablets.\" Ranges are typically used in instructions.\nonsetString\nString\n0..1\nA sequence of Unicode characters to convey the estimated onset of when the condition started.\nabatementDateTime\ndateTime\n0..1\nEstimated or actual date or date-time when the Condition statement was resolved or in remission.\nabatementQuantity\nQuantity\n0..1\nThere shall be a code if there is a value and it shall be an expression of time. If system is present, it shall be UCUM. If value is present, it shall be positive. The context of use may frequently define what kind of quantity this is and therefore what kind of units can be used. In this case, it is used to indicate when the condition was resolved or in remission.\nabatementBoolean\nBoolean\n0..1\nThere is no explicit distinction between resolution and remission because in many cases the distinction is not clear. Age is generally used when the patient reports an age at which the Condition abated. If there is no abatement element, it is unknown whether the condition was resolved or in remission; applications and users should generally assume that the condition is still valid.\nabatementPeriod\nPeriod\n0..1\nA time period defined by a start and end date/time. A period specifies a range of times for if or when the condition was resolved or in remission.\nabatementRange\nHl7.Fhir.Model.Range\n0..1\nA set of ordered quantity values defined by a low and high limit. A range specifies a set of possible values; usually, one value from the range applies. In this case, the range defines if and when the condition was resolved or in remission.\nabatementString\nString\n0..1\nA sequence of unicode characters to convey when the condition was resolved or in remission.\nstage\n0..1\nA set of codified values for which the conformance is example and is typically used to indicate stages of cancer and other conditions. More information can be found at the\n    55→FHIR website\n    56→.\n    57→The InPracSys FHIR API is based on FHIR V4, of the FHIR standard. Updates and definitions for use of the standard can be found on the Link:\n    58→FHIR V4\n    59→.\n    60→The EHI export contains available electronic health information for a single patient or multiple patients in computable file format. The export(s) can be downloaded as a zip file containing .xml file(s).\n    61→Security\n    62→Like many RESTful APIs, the InPracSys FHIR API uses OAuth 2 for security. This means that when making calls to any resource with the InPracSys FHIR API, you must pass a Bearer token. This token is passed in the Authorization Header.\n    63→Authorization: Bearer eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsIng1dCI6IjJaUXBKM1VwYmpBWVhZR2FYRUpsOGxWMF...\n    64→To obtain a Bearer token, you must call an Authorization Server. The authorization server typically exposes two endpoints:\n    65→authorize: typically used to confirm the user’s credentials\n    66→token: used to obtain the Bearer token\n    67→As per the FHIR specification, the InPracSys FHIR API supports JSON. we limit our examples to JSON.\n    68→Overview\n    69→Step 1: Search for a patient\n    70→Now that we have the Bearer token, we can call the API. More information can be found at the\nFHIR website\n.\nThe InPracSys FHIR API is based on FHIR V4, of the FHIR standard. Updates and definitions for use of the standard can be found on the Link:\nFHIR V4\n.\nThe EHI export contains available electronic health information for a single patient or multiple patients in computable file format. The export(s) can be downloaded as a zip file containing .xml file(s).\nSecurity\nLike many RESTful APIs, the InPracSys FHIR API uses OAuth 2 for security. This means that when making calls to any resource with the InPracSys FHIR API, you must pass a Bearer token. This token is passed in the Authorization Header.\nAuthorization: Bearer eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsIng1dCI6IjJaUXBKM1VwYmpBWVhZR2FYRUpsOGxWMF...\nTo obtain a Bearer token, you must call an Authorization Server. The authorization server typically exposes two endpoints:\nauthorize: typically used to confirm the user’s credentials\ntoken: used to obtain the Bearer token\nAs per the FHIR specification, the InPracSys FHIR API supports JSON. we limit our examples to JSON.\nOverview\nStep 1: Search for a patient\nNow that we have the Bearer token, we can call the API. We will use it to search for a patient called Jamie.\nGET https://fhirips.azurehealthcareapis.com/Patient?given=Jamie\nThis will return a collection of patient references. FHIR detail: FHIR returns this collection as a Bundle. When writing your client you will need to be aware of this detail, but we will gloss over that for now.\n{\n  \"resourceType\": \"Bundle\",\n  \"TotalElement\": \"4\",\n  \"entry\":[\n   {\n ClientID you will get the accesstoken.\nStep 2: Use the above information to obtain a bearer token\nThe important pieces of information here are\nI) The logical ID is found as the result of a search.\nGET https://fhirips.azurehealthcareapis.com/Patient?given=Jamie&family=Rosdel\nName\nType\nCardinality\nDescription\nidentifier\nIdentifier\n0..*\nPatient's identifier. Patients are usually assigned a specific numerical identifier that is unique within the system.\nactive\nboolean\n0..1\nIs the patient's record active? The default value is true. Need to be able to mark a patient record as not to be used because it was created in error. If a record is inactive, and linked to an active record, then future patient/record updates should occur on the other patient.\nname\nHumanName\n0..*\nName associated with the patient.\ntelecom\nContactPoint\n0..*\nPatient contact communication detail. This indicates the value in any kind of telecom details field for the patient. If capturing a phone, fax, or similar contact point, the value is a properly formatted telephone number according to ITU-T E.123. However, this is frequently not possible due to legacy data and/or clerical practices when recording contact details. For this reason, phone, fax, page, and email addresses are not handled as formal URLs.\ngender\ncode\n0..1\nPatient's gender. Returns Male, Female, Other, or Unknown. The codes shall be taken from the AllergyIntoleranceStatus value set which includes: Active, Unconfirmed, Confirmed, Inactive, Resolved, Refuted, and Entered in Error. Decision support would typically raise alerts for Unconfirmed, Confirmed, and Resolved and ignore a Refuted reaction. In particular, Refuted may be useful for reconciliation of the Adverse Reaction List. Conformance is required and as such, some implementations may choose to make this field mandatory. Decision support would typically raise alerts for Unconfirmed, Confirmed, and Resolved and ignore a Refuted reaction. In particular, Refuted may be useful for reconciliation of the Adverse Reaction List. Conformance is required and as such, some implementations may choose to make this field mandatory. If the diagnostic procedure was performed on the patient, this is the time it was performed. If there are specimens, the diagnostically relevant time can be derived from the specimen collection times, but the specimen information is not always available, and the exact relationship between the specimens and the diagnostically relevant time is not always automatic. If the start element is missing, the start of the period is not known. This value set indicates the allowed vital sign result types. The vocabulary selected for this value set aligns with requirements in the Meaningful Use (MU) Stage 2. Note the concept Blood pressure systolic and diastolic (55284-4) is used to group the related observations Systolic blood pressure (8480-6) and Diastolic blood pressure (8462-4). The patient, or group of patients, location, or device whose characteristics (direct or indirect) are described by the observation and into whose record the observation is placed. Indirect characteristics may be those of a specimen, fetus, donor, other observer (for example a relative or EMT), or any observation made about the subject. Observations have no value if you don't know who or what they're about. Note: One would expect this element to be a cardinality of 1..1. The only circumstance in which the subject can be missing is when the observation is made by a device that does not know the patient. For some observations it may be important to know the link between the vital sign and a particular encounter.\n  1170→effectiveDateTime\n  1171→dateTime\n  1172→0..1\n  1173→Clinically relevant time/time-period for observation. Often just a dateTime for Vital Signs. Knowing when an observation was deemed true is important to its relevance as well as determining trends. At least a date should be present unless this observation is a historical report.\n  1174→effectivePeriod\n  1175→Period\n  1176→0..1\n  1177→Clinically relevant time/time-period for observation. Often a dateTime for Vital Signs is preferred but if it is a historical instance, then a time period is sufficient.\n  1178→issued\n  1179→Hl7.Fhir.Model.Instant\n  1180→0..1\n  1181→Date/Time this was made available.\n  1182→performer\n  1183→Reference(Practitioner, Organization, Patient, RelatedPerson)\n  1184→0..*\n  1185→Who is responsible for the observation or obtaining the vital sign. May give a degree of confidence in the observation and also indicates where follow-up questions should be directed.\n  1186→valueQuantity\n  1187→Quantity\n  1188→0..1\n  1189→Vital Sign Value recorded with UCUM. Common UCUM units for recording Vital Signs. The codes shall be taken from Common UCUM units as defined in http://unitsofmeasure.org Examples include % (percent), cm (centimeter), kg (kilogram), mm(Hg) (millimeter of mercury), /min (per minute) and kg/m2 (kilogram). Note: Normally, an observation will have either a value or a set of related observations. A few observations (e.g. Apgar score) may have both a value and related observations (for an Apgar score, the observations from which the measure is derived). If a value is present, the datatype for this element should be determined by Observation.code. This element has a variable name depending on the type as follows: valueQuantity, valueCodeableConcept, valueString, valueRange, valueRatio, valueSampledData, valueAttachment, valueTime, valueDateTime, or valuePeriod. (The name format is \"�value\" + the type name\" with a capital on the first letter of the type).\n  1190→valueQuantity.value\n  1191→http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.valueQuantity.value\n  1192→0..1\n  1193→The value of the measured amount. The value includes an implicit precision in the presentation of the value. Precision is handled implicitly in almost all cases of measurement. The implicit precision in the value should always be honored. Monetary values have their own rules for handling precision (refer to standard accounting text books).\n  1194→valueQuantity.unit\n  1195→http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.valueQuantity.unit\n  1196→0..1\n  1197→A human-readable form of the unit. There are many representations for units of measure and in many contexts, particular representations are fixed and required. For example, mcg for micrograms.\n  1198→valueQuantity.system\n  1199→http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.valueQuantity.system\n  1200→0..1\n  1201→The identification of the system that provides the coded form of the unit. Need to know the system that defines the coded form of the unit. Fixed value http://unitsofmeasure.org.\n  1202→valueQuantity.code\n  1203→http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.valueQuantity.code\n  1204→0..1\n  1205→Coded responses from the common UCUM units for vital signs value set. Need a computable form of the unit that is fixed across all forms. UCUM provides this for quantities, but SNOMED CT provides many units of interest. The preferred system is UCUM, but SNOMED CT can also be used (for customary units) or ISO 4217 for currency. The context of use may additionally require a code from a particular system.\n  1206→dataAbsentReason\n  1207→CodeableConcept\n  1208→0..1\n  1209→Provides a reason why the expected value in the element Observation.value[x] is missing. Codes specifying why the result (Observation.value[x]) is missing. The codes shall be taken from Observation Value Absent Reason value set, however other codes may be used where these codes are not suitable. This value set contains 9 concepts. For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-valueabsentreason.\n  1210→interpretation\n  1211→CodeableConcept\n  1212→0..1\n  1213→This value set defines the set of codes that can be used to indicate the meaning/use of a reference range. The value set is extensible and contains 33 concepts. Examples include A (Abnormal), H (High), L (Low), and N (Normal). For more information on this value set, see http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-interpretation.\n  1214→referenceRange\n  1215→BackboneElement http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.referenceRange\n  1216→0..*\n  1217→Guidance on how to interpret the value by comparison to a normal or recommended range. Knowing what values are considered \"normal\" can help evaluate the significance of a particular result. Need to be able to provide multiple reference ranges for different contexts. Most observations only have one generic reference range. Systems may choose to restrict to only supplying the relevant reference range based on knowledge about the patient (for example, specific to the patient's age, gender, weight, and other factors), but this may not be possible or appropriate. Whenever more than one reference range is supplied, the differences between them should be provided in the reference range and/or age properties.\n  1218→— referenceRange.Low\n  1219→SimpleQuantity http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.referenceRange.low\n  1220→0..1\n  1221→Indication that the vital result is lower than the defined reference range. Binding is common UCUM units for recording Vital Signs.\n  1222→— referenceRange.High\n  1223→SimpleQuantity http://www.hl7.org/fhir/daf/daf-vitalsigns-definitions.html#daf-vitalsigns.Observation.referenceRange.high\n  1224→0..1\n  1225→Indication that the vital result is higher than the defined reference range. Binding is common UCUM units for recording Vital Signs.\n  1226→Respiratory rate\n  1227→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Respiratory_Rate_Example\n  1228→0..1\n  1229→Recorded under LOINC Code 9279-1 using UOM of (breaths)/min.\n  1230→Heart rate\n  1231→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Heart_Rate_Example\n  1232→0..1\n  1233→Recorded under LOINC Code 8867-4 using UOM of (beats)/min.\n  1234→Oxygen saturation\n  1235→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Oxygen_Saturation_Example\n  1236→0..1\n  1237→Recorded under LOINC Code 59408-5 using UOM of % Oxygen saturation in Arterial blood by Pulse oximetry.\n  1238→Body temperature\n  1239→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Body_Temperature_Example\n  1240→0..1\n  1241→Recorded under LOINC Code 8310-5 using UOM of Cel or [degF].\n  1242→Body height\n  1243→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Body_height_Example\n  1244→0..1\n  1245→Recorded under LOINC Code 8302-2 using UOM cm or [in].\n  1246→Body weight\n  1247→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Body_Weight_Example\n  1248→0..1\n  1249→Recorded under LOINC Code 29463-7 using UOM g, kg or lb.\n  1250→Body mass index\n  1251→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Body_Mass_Example\n  1252→0..1\n  1253→Recorded under LOINC Code 39156-5 using UOM kg/m2.\n  1254→Blood pressure systolic and diastolic\n  1255→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Blood_Pressure_Example\n  1256→1..1\n  1257→Recorded under LOINC Code 55284-4 using UOM mm[Hg].\n  1258→Systolic blood pressure\n  1259→http://argonautwiki.hl7.org/index.php?title=Vital_Signs_Blood_Pressure_Example\n  1260→1..1\n  1261→Recorded under LOINC Code 8480-6 using UOM mm[Hg]. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/care-plan-status.\n  1451→category\n  1452→CodeableConcept\n  1453→0..*\n  1454→Options could include Problem, Health Concern, Care Team, or Assessment and Plan of Treatment. Roles may be inferred by type of practitioner. These are relationships that hold only within the context of the care team. General relationships should be handled as properties of the patient resource directly. See below for more information.\nA DAF DiagnosticReport is returned.\nName\nType\nCardinality\nDescription\nidentifier\n0..*\nLocal ID assigned to the report by the order filler, usually by the information system of the diagnostic service provider. You must know what identifier to use when making queries about this report from the source laboratory and for linking to the report outside FHIR context. Alternate name: ReportID.\nstatus\ncode\n1..1\nStatus of the diagnostic report as a whole. Diagnostic services routinely issue provisional/incomplete reports, and sometimes withdraw previously released reports. This is labeled as \"Is Modifier\" because applications need to take appropriate action if a report is withdrawn. The codes shall be taken from the DiagnosticReportStatus value set, which includes the following statuses: Registered, Partial, Final, Corrected, Appended, Cancelled, and Entered-in-Error. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/diagnostic-report-status.\ncategory\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nCode that classifies the clinical discipline, department, or diagnostic service that created the report. For example, cardiology, biochemistry, hematology, or MRI. This is used for searching, sorting, and displaying purposes. The level of granularity is defined by the category concepts in the DiagnosticServiceSectionCodes value set. More filtering is performed using the metadata and/or terminology hierarchy in DiagnosticReport.code. Alternate names: Department, Sub-department, service, discipline. Example codes include: AU- Audiology, CH- Chemistry, MB- Microbiology, and HM- Hematology. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/diagnostic-service-sections.\ncode\nCodeableConcept\n1..1\nTest, panel, or battery that was ordered. The typical patterns for codes are: 1) a LOINC code either as a translation from a \"local\" code or as a primary code, 2) a local code only if no suitable LOINC exists, or 3) both the local and the LOINC translation. Systems shall be capable of sending the local code if one exists. The codes shall be taken from US Laboratory Observation Profile Observation Name Codes. Other codes may be used where these codes are not suitable. This value set has more than 1000 codes. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/report-codes.\nsubject\nReference(Patient, Group, Device, Location)\n1..1\nSubject of the report. Usually this is a patient. However, diagnostic services also perform analyses on specimens collected from a variety of other sources.\nencounter\nReference(Encounter)\n0..1\nLink to the healthcare event (encounter) when the order was made.\neffectiveDateTime\ndateTime\n1..1\nSpecimen Collection Datetime which is the physically relevant dateTime for laboratory tests. If the diagnostic procedure was performed on the patient, this is the time it was performed. If there are specimens, the diagnostically relevant time can be derived from the specimen collection times, but the specimen information is not always available, and the exact relationship between the specimens and the diagnostically relevant time is not always automatic.\neffectivePeriod\nPeriod\n1..1\nSpecimen Collection Period which is the physically relevant dateTime for laboratory tests. If the diagnostic procedure was performed on the patient, this is the time it was performed. If there are specimens, the diagnostically relevant time can be derived from the specimen collection times, but the specimen information is not always available, and the exact relationship between the specimens and the diagnostically relevant time is not always automatic. If the start element is missing, the start of the period is not known. If the end element is missing, it means that the period is ongoing, or the start may be in the past, and the end date in the future, which means that period is expected/planned to end at the specified time.\nissued\nHl7.Fhir.Model.Instant\n1..1\nDate and time that this version of the report was released from the source diagnostic service. Clinicians must be able to check the date that the report was released. This may be different from the update time of the resource itself, because that is the status of the record (potentially a secondary copy), not the actual release time of the report. Alternate names: Date Created, Date published, Date Issued.\nperformer\nReference(Practitioner, Organization)\n1..1\nDiagnostic service that is responsible for issuing the report. This is helpful to know who to contact if there are queries about the results. You may need to track the source of reports for secondary data analysis. This is not necessarily the source of the atomic data items. It is the entity that takes responsibility for the clinical report. Alternate names: Laboratory, Service, Practitioner, Department, Company.\nrequest\nReference(DiagnosticOrder, ProcedureRequest, ReferralRequest)\n1..*\nDetails concerning a test or procedure requested. You need to be able to track completion of requests based on reports issued and also to report what diagnostic tests were requested (not always the same as what is delivered). You need to be able to track completion of requests based on reports issued and also to report what diagnostic tests were requested (not always the same as what is delivered).\nspecimen\nReference(Specimen)\n0..*\nDetails about the specimens on which this diagnostic report is based. If the specimen is sufficiently specified with a code in the test result name, then this additional data may be redundant. If there are multiple specimens, these may be represented per observation or group.\nresult\nReference(Observation)\n0..*\nObservations that are part of this diagnostic report. Observations can be simple name/value pairs (for example, \"atomic\" results), or they can be grouping observations that include references to other members of the group (such as \"panels\"). You need to support individual results, or report groups of results, where the result grouping is arbitrary, but meaningful. This structure is recursive in that observations can contain observations. Alternate names: Data, Atomic Value, Result, Atomic result, Data, Test, Analyte, Battery, or Organizer.\nimagingStudy\nReference(ImagingStudy, ImagingObjectSelection)\n0..*\nOne or more links to full details of any imaging performed during the diagnostic investigation. Typically, this is imaging performed by DICOM enabled modalities, but this is not required. A fully enabled PACS viewer can use this information to provide views of the source images. ImagingStudy and ImageObjectStudy and the image element are somewhat overlapping - typically, the list of image references in the image element will also be found in one of the imaging study resources. However each caters to different types of displays for different types of purposes. Neither, either, or both may be provided.\nimage\n0..*\nList of key images associated with this report. The images are generally created during the diagnostic process, and may be directly of the patient, or of treated specimens (for example, slides of interest).\nimage.comment\nstring\n0..1\nComment about the image. Typically this is used to provide an explanation for why the image is included, or to draw the viewer's attention to important features. The provider of the report should make a comment about each image included in the report. The comment should be displayed with the image. It would be common for the report to include additional discussion of the image contents in other sections such as the conclusion.\nimage.link\nReference(Media)\n1..1\nReference to the image source.\nconclusion\nstring\n0..1\nConcise and clinically contextualized narrative interpretation of the diagnostic report. You need to be able to provide a conclusion that is not lost among the basic result data. Typically, a report is either [all data, no narrative (e.g. Core lab)] or [a mix of data with some concluding narrative (e.g. Structured Pathology Report, Bone Density)], or [all narrative (e.g. typical imaging report, histopathology)]. In all of these cases, the narrative goes in \"text\".\ncodedDiagnosis\nCodeableConcept\n0..*\nCodes for the conclusion which are SNOMED CT findings codes provided as adjunct diagnosis to the report. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-category\ncode\nCodeableConcept\n1..1\nThis identifies the vital sign result type. Coded responses are from C-CDA Vital Sign Results. 1. Shall contain exactly one [1..1] code, where the @code should be selected from ValueSet HITSP Vital Sign Result Type. This value set indicates the allowed vital sign result types. The vocabulary selected for this value set aligns with requirements in the Meaningful Use (MU) Stage 2. Note the concept Blood pressure systolic and diastolic (55284-4) is used to group the related observations Systolic blood pressure (8480-6) and Diastolic blood pressure (8462-4). It shall not be used alone, but both 8480-6 and 8462-2 shall also be valued. The codes shall be taken from C-CDA Vital Sign Result; other codes may be used where these codes are not suitable. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/observation-codes\nsubject\nReference(Patient, Group, Device, Location)\n0..1\nWho and/or what this vital is for. The patient, or group of patients, location, or device whose characteristics (direct or indirect) are described by the observation and into whose record the observation is placed. Indirect characteristics may be those of a specimen, fetus, donor, other observer (for example a relative or EMT), or any observation made about the subject. Observations have no value if you don't know who or what they're about. Note: One would expect this element to be a cardinality of 1..1. The only circumstance in which the subject can be missing is when the observation is made by a device that does not know the patient. In this case, the observation shall be matched to a patient through some context/channel matching technique, and at this point, the observation should be updated.\nencounter\nReference(Encounter)\n0..1\nThe healthcare event (for example, a patient and healthcare provider interaction) during which this vital was obtained. Note: Normally, an observation will have either a value or a set of related observations. A few observations (e.g. Apgar score) may have both a value and related observations (for an Apgar score, the observations from which the measure is derived). Knowing what values are considered \"normal\" can help evaluate the significance of a particular result. Need to be able to provide multiple reference ranges for different contexts. Most observations only have one generic reference range. Systems may choose to restrict to only supplying the relevant reference range based on knowledge about the patient (for example, specific to the patient's age, gender, weight, and other factors), but this may not be possible or appropriate. This is a business identifier, not a resource identifier. For example, in CDA documents or in written/printed documentation.\nsubject\nReference(Patient, Group)\n0..1\nWho the care plan is for. This identifies the patient or group whose intended care is described by the plan.\nstatus\ncode\n1..1\nIndicates hether the plan is currently acted upon, represents future intentions, or is now a historical record. It allows clinicians to determine whether the plan is actionable or not. Conformance is required, and the valid statuses include: Proposed, Pending, Active, Completed, and Cancelled. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/care-plan-status.\ncategory\nCodeableConcept\n0..*\nIdentifies what kind of plan this is to support differentiation between multiple co-existing plans. For example, \"Home health\", \"psychiatric\", \"asthma\", \"disease management\", \"wellness plan\", and so forth. There may be multiple axis of categorization, and one plan may serve multiple purposes. In some cases, this may be redundant with references to CarePlan.concern. This value set contains 21 concepts. For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/care-plan-category.\nnarrative summary\nstring\n0..1\nText or HTML description of the assessment and plan. CarePlan.text.status is either Generated or Additional. This tool uses Generated. Dates shall be valid dates.\nstartCodeableConcept\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nWhen the goal pursuit begins. (For that, use the provenance resource.)\npriority\nCodeableConcept\n0..1\nIdentifies the mutually agreed level of importance associated with reaching and/or sustaining the goal. This is used for sorting and presenting goals. Extensions are available to track priorities as established by each participant. For example, priority from the patient's perspective, different practitioners' perspectives, or family member's perspectives. The ordinal extension on coding can be used to convey a numerically comparable ranking to priority. Conformance is preferred and defines the following codes: High, Medium, and Low. Different coding systems may use \"low value=important.\" For more information on this value set, see: http://hl7.org/fhir/ValueSet/goal-priority.\naddresses\nReference(Condition, Observation, MedicationStatement, NutritionOrder, ProcedureRequest, RiskAssessment)\n0..*\nIdentified conditions and other health record elements that are intended to be addressed by the goal.
